# **Technocapitalism** refers to a contemporary economic and social system characterized by the dominance of technology-driven capital, where [technological innovation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technological_innovation "Technological innovation") becomes a central component of [economic growth](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_growth "Economic growth") and [wealth accumulation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_accumulation "Capital accumulation"). This term encapsulates the interplay between [technology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technology "Technology") and [capitalism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capitalism "Capitalism"), highlighting how advancements in technology influence economic structures, [labor markets](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Labor_markets "Labor markets"), and [social relations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_relations "Social relations"). A significant aspect of technocapitalism is the rise of the intangible economy, which is marked by the increasing importance of non-physical assets such as [intellectual property](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intellectual_property "Intellectual property"), [brand value](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brand_valuation "Brand valuation"), and digital services. This shift has led to new forms of economic centralization, where a few [tech giants](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tech_Giants "Tech Giants") dominate markets due to their ability to scale rapidly and leverage synergies across different sectors.
